===  MODERATOR COMMENT ===

Dear HelpMates,

Well, the first thing I noticed, sitting down to do this issue, is
that I'd forgotten to order my 2003 Chase's Calendar, which is my
source for all those holidays, each day
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0071390987/ref=nosimmywishlis
tA (Sheesh. Where did the time go?! I usually order it in October.)

Then, I must tell you about having breakfast with Raleigh Pinksy
yesterday morning. http://promoteyourself.com  You may remember that
last week, I was feeling so sheepish about letting her down? (I had
bought some particualarly interesting PR URLs last year that we'd
planned to develop - and I've just not had time to do it.)

Well, she's got two great projects she's working on, and has invited
me to participate. That means, I really MUST finish the book I
started in August, about the 10 businesses to start online without a
dime! (I'd better call Nancy Preiss, this week, to help compile the
rest of the book. http://campaignsthatwork.com/ so Serenata
http://serenata.nu can format the e-book. She's getting really good
at it!)

But, a lot of my time of the past couple of weeks has been spent in
total frustration with our server move.  Rob Marlbrough, Jr.
http://webwizards.net went out of his way to put a special package
together for me, to address my bizarre server needs. (Uh, aside from
my own stuff, I am hosting sites for 'partners' or friends who need
direct access to their own control panels, without giving them
access to my sites.)

His new servers, with their very interesting control panels look
like their features will be quite a timesaver - once we get all the
moves completed. In the meantime, it's been quite a headache. I am
sure that Rob is sorry he ever started this. He's spent so much time
sorting out the different needs. And mail has been lost. (So, if you
sent me anything since about mid-December and haven't heard back,
please, do resend it. Thanks.)

But dealing  with someone like Rob, despite my frustration, and
perhaps my sometimes less than kind demeanor, really is a joy. I
KNOW that I can count on him to sort it all out. I know that he has
stayed up nights to work on my sites. I know that he will do
everything he can to make me happy. (Well, not everything... Rick
might object.)

And there are little bright flashes through this adventure. Like
yesterday, when I couldn't figure out how to FTP to a site that had
just been moved to it's own server via my WS-FTP program. And I was
in a hurry, so I didn't have time to figure what I'd done wrong.
Rob's control panel has an FTP feature built-in. I noticed a little
drop-down menu on the bottom corner of the page and saw an 'edit'
function.

For some you, this is no big deal, but for me, WOW! What a treat. I
was able to click on the page I wanted and edit the code right in
the browser. I didn't do anything fancy, but I needed to fix a
problem on my appointment page
http://taxanxiety.com/appointment.html (no it's not linked anywhere
on the site - my clients get the address from a letter or my e-mails
only to them) it took me about three minutes AND to download the
revision to my computer. I really that feature. (OK, so you've been
using this for years. But, hey, small things amuse small minds. OK?)
So, Rob, if I haven't said it before - THANK YOU.

One of the other interesting things I discovered in his e-mail tool
is that I can build a custom mailing list, just by using the
'forwarding' function. It looks like I can add as many people as I
want (no doubt there is a limit) and name the list. And this is
aside from some of the other mailing list tools.

And speaking of spam...the webmail tool is really interesting. Yes,
I know, who wants to use webmail. BUT, it has spam filters I can
customise. So, I can set it to screen out entire URLs, or just the
contents of the mail. Running that before I download my mail will
screen out the junk. Then, I can download the real mail. And it's
faster than the old version.

I can hardly wait to see what else I can do.

Sorry to go on. But, I like clever features when I can see how
clearly they're going to help save my time during this coming tax
season.

And speaking of marketing. You never know how long it will take the
seeds you sow to sprout.

About 10 years ago, I started teaching classes at UCLA to help tax
pros pass the IRS exam to become Enrolled Agents.
http://taxmama.com/Articles-Pro/EA_1.htm

I got a call yesterday from one of the students in my second class,
from 9 years ago. She had retired and moved away last year. Two of
her clients refused to move on - so she called me yesterday about
referring them to me.

Frankly, with the sale of a big chunk of my tax practice, I had
really expected to have a reduced load this tax season. But, people
keep calling. I've gotten more new clients in the past month
(supposed to be a slow/dead time?) than any month all year. What's
going on????

We have a new site to review. What a coincidence, after writing all
the above, it's a webhost. And it sounds interesting. (look at her
stats program) So, please DO go and review it.

But, that brings me to just one last thing. (I know, this has gone
on waaaay too long, already.) Someone wrote to me telling me that,
try as she might, she couldn't find a link or e-mail address to
submit her site for review.

So, just a reminder, my friends. The guidelines are above, in every
issue, labeled in the table of contents via the deliberately obscure
title - SUBMISSION GUIDELINES. And the link to submit is hidden,
buried even, in each issue, where you would least expect to find it,
as the very first line in the 'SITE EVALUATIONS' section, where it
reads  'SUBMIT YOUR SITE HERE'.

Your Humble Guide,

Eva Rosenberg
http://taxmama.com  http://workinghumor.com
http://ebookad.com/eb.php3?ebookid=15045

P.S. I'm starting to get some of your 2002 reflections.
Remember to send yours in to me at
mailto:ihelpdesk@adventive.com?Subject=2002Summation

And your Thanks to
mailto:ihelpdesk@adventive.com?Subject=Thanks


