This Week's Site #1  http://www.reenee.net
Web Host
Please send all correspondence using this address
mailto:serena@reenee.net?CC=ihelpdesk@adventive.com&subject=Reenee


From: "Serena M. Giddens"
mailto:serena@reenee.net?CC=ihelpdesk@adventive.com&subject=Reenee

URL:  http://www.reenee.net

Reenee.net is a web hosting service, providing web services for
business and personal site owners.   My daughter, Shauna, and I
started our business on March 1, 2002, with our main goal being
to establish a good customer base and income for the years to come.

That's very important, as I will lose almost half of my current
disability income at retirement age.  I will not be able to survive
on that reduced fixed income, so I very much need to develop a
dependable source of income within the next 10 years.  The plan
is to not take any salary from the business for several years, at
least not until there is sufficient funding to meet ongoing
business expenses, growth of services, etc., funneling income
right back into the business to optimize growth and income before
the elapse of ten years.

Hopefully the business will thrive, my needs will be met, and
Shauna will have an already established business in time to come.

Fortunately, while I'm pretty much a housebound disabled person,
I can sit at the computer (I have two) on a flexible schedule
(related to physical limitations), have a background in computer-
related tech support (both in off-line businesses and for another
web host.)  In fact, my experience in tech support at that web
host later motivated me to choose web hosting as a business as I
really enjoyed working in that arena.  In addition to being a
substantial life line for me, I love all things computer-related,
including web design and providing a safe haven for the online
communities to come and play.

(I created and have maintained since 1996 a personal web site,
SERENA's WORLD (http://www.serena1.com) - a kid-safe entertainment/
activities site - which is fairly popular, especially in the
Christmas season (but really all year), and utilized by a lot of
schooldistricts, private and public schools, libraries, media rooms
and, of course, families.  In fact SERENA's WORLD received two very
generous donations in December to keep it on line through the
Christmas holidays when  it ran out of its 20-gig bandwidth
allotment for the month mid-way through December.  SW is 200+ pages,
so I am familiar with managing a large site.)


My main problem is in getting the word out about my business site
and services on a non-existent advertising budget.  But I don't want
to have a bunch of banner ads on my site in an effort to accomplish
this. I've submitted to search engines, listed my site with some
other business sites, and advertised it on my personal site (since
it gets a fair amount of traffic).  I'm also in the process of
contacting folks I used to work with in the legal community to let
them know I'm here and seeking new clients.

I worked at a large law firm in Dallas and many of those attorneys
who are familiar with my work ethic, quality and reliability of work
have left and formed their own law firms.  I'm a natural to service
law firms with my background in legal since 1966.  The law firm
from which I retired disabled plans to have me design a new web site
for them and host it - that project begins in a few weeks, and I
have a couple of other business clients already, but the business
must definitely grow to meet the ongoing expenses of maintaining my
web hosting business.

I'm still operating in the red.  I know these things take time, but
I must grow the business sufficiently within the next year to at
least offset my monthly business expenses which was and is funded
from my own fixed income and credit.

At any rate, I just received my I-HelpDesk_WebReview Digest, Issue 1155
which mentioned WebReviews, so I thought I'd submit and see what I can
learn to better equip our business for successfully meeting our goals.

Thanks for this opportunity.

Sincerely,

Serena M. Giddens
Reenee.net, Inc.
http://www.reenee.net

